<p>These numbers total up to 45 hours 45 minutes that I can work with. This is how much time I have to get 30 hours of work done. This also includes fitting in exceptions (such as my project, but more prominent may be the need for breaks and making up for the lack of sleep).</p>
<h3>Setup</h3>
<p>I'm doing this WES in a room different than the one I usually work in (or waste in, to be more accurate). This simple room just contains a desk with my laptop (and my laptop accessories), a small bookshelf (which holds the textbooks I want to work through), a recording setup (for streaming) and a pile of mattresses (for sleeping). I'm concerned for my health related to my posture (which is why I'm thinking about buying a standing desk/a desk with adjustable height).</p>
<h3>Other things to keep in mind</h3>
<p>My schedule asks for me to wake up and sleep at some extreme times (waking up and sleeping <em>extremely early,</em> to be exact). I'll have to try my best to make as little noise as possible so I don't wake others up (this includes my alarm!). I also need to make sure that my stream goes well (i.e. it doesn't fail, my phone's charger doesn't get disconnected, somebody doesn't call me in the middle of the stream, etc.). I also don't want to fall asleep in the stream (that would be pretty embarrassing), and I also want to make sure that my head doesn't block the content (and I would like it to stay out of the stream as much as possible). However, even with these setbacks that live streaming provides, I still strongly believe that it is an extremely powerful tool and the benefits it provides far outweigh the extra management and effort I need to put in.</p>
<h3>Conclusion</h3>
<p>Even though my motive is to get my work done with this WES, I don't think that I'm the only one capable of doing such a thing. I don't think I have some special gene that makes me more successful in doing these extremes and I believe that everyone can do something similar to my idea of a super study session. The big issue is, society isn't as keen as learning as it once was. Social media has taken over and has dragged heads into a world where they don't really get much done. Society has marketed weekends as 'getaway time,' and the WES aims to change that mentality. I believe the weekends should be a time where we ought to learn more than what school limits and to push our efforts and motives beyond just getting a good mark. The WES has potential, not just for me, but for anyone who seeks to become much more than they once will have been.</p>
<p><em>"We cannot become what we want to be by remaining what we are."</em> <strong>- Max DePree</strong></p>
